# React Router v6+

## The Mental Model — Router as Component Tree

React Router maps URL paths to component trees. Think of routes like a directory structure: the URL `/dashboard/settings` maps to a nested component tree `<App> → <Dashboard> → <Settings>`.

```
URL: /dashboard/settings

Component tree rendered:
  <RouterProvider>
    <Root>
      <Nav />
      <Outlet />           ← renders matched child route
        <Dashboard>
          <Outlet />       ← renders matched grandchild route
            <Settings />
        </Dashboard>
    </Root>
  </RouterProvider>
```

## Setting Up Routes (v6 data router style)

```tsx
import { createBrowserRouter, RouterProvider } from 'react-router-dom';

const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/',
    element: <Root />,
    errorElement: <ErrorBoundary />,
    children: [
      { index: true, element: <Home /> },          // /
      {
        path: 'dashboard',
        element: <Dashboard />,
        children: [
          { index: true, element: <DashHome /> },  // /dashboard
          { path: 'settings', element: <Settings /> },  // /dashboard/settings
          { path: 'user/:id', element: <UserDetail /> }, // /dashboard/user/42
        ],
      },
      { path: '*', element: <NotFound /> },          // catch-all 404
    ],
  },
]);

function App() {
  return <RouterProvider router={router} />;
}
```

## Outlet — where child routes render

```tsx
// Parent route component must render <Outlet />
// where it wants its child route to appear

function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <div className="dashboard-layout">
      <DashboardNav />
      <main>
        <Outlet />  {/* /dashboard renders DashHome, /dashboard/settings renders Settings */}
      </main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Route Parameters and URL Search Params

```tsx
// Route: path: 'user/:id'
function UserDetail() {
  const { id } = useParams();           // 'id' from URL segment
  const [searchParams, setSearchParams] = useSearchParams();
  const tab = searchParams.get('tab') ?? 'profile'; // ?tab=orders

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>User {id}</h1>
      <Tabs current={tab} onChange={tab => setSearchParams({ tab })} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Loaders — data fetching before render

Loaders run before the component renders, so the component always has data — no loading spinners needed in the component itself.

```tsx
// Define loader alongside route
const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: 'dashboard/user/:id',
    element: <UserDetail />,
    loader: async ({ params }) => {
      const user = await fetch(`/api/users/${params.id}`).then(r => r.json());
      if (!user) throw new Response('Not Found', { status: 404 });
      return user;
    },
  },
]);

// Component reads loader data — always defined, no loading state
function UserDetail() {
  const user = useLoaderData() as User;
  return <div>{user.name}</div>;
}
```

```
Navigation lifecycle with loader:
  User clicks link to /dashboard/user/42
           │
           ▼
  Router calls loader({ params: { id: '42' } })
           │
           ▼
  Loader fetches data
           │
       ┌───┴───┐
    success   error
       │          └──► errorElement renders
       ▼
  Component renders with useLoaderData()
  Navigation URL changes to /dashboard/user/42
```

## Navigation — Link, NavLink, useNavigate

```tsx
import { Link, NavLink, useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

// Declarative navigation
<Link to='/dashboard'>Dashboard</Link>

// NavLink adds active class when URL matches
<NavLink to='/dashboard' className={({ isActive }) => isActive ? 'active' : ''}>
  Dashboard
</NavLink>

// Programmatic navigation
function LoginForm() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  async function handleSubmit(data: LoginData) {
    await login(data);
    navigate('/dashboard', { replace: true }); // replace history entry
  }
}
```

## Protected Routes Pattern

```tsx
// Pattern 1: wrapper component
function ProtectedRoute({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const { user } = useAuth();
  if (!user) return <Navigate to='/login' replace />;
  return <>{children}</>;
}

// Pattern 2: loader-based (preferred in v6.4+)
const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: 'dashboard',
    loader: async () => {
      const user = await getUser();
      if (!user) throw redirect('/login'); // redirects in loader
      return user;
    },
    element: <Dashboard />,
  },
]);
```

## useLocation and useMatch

```tsx
function NavItem({ to }: { to: string }) {
  const location = useLocation();
  // location.pathname, location.search, location.hash, location.state

  const match = useMatch({ path: to, end: true });
  // match is non-null when URL matches

  return <a className={match ? 'active' : ''} href={to}>{to}</a>;
}

// Pass state between routes
navigate('/confirm', { state: { orderId: 42 } });
const { state } = useLocation(); // { orderId: 42 } on the target page
```

## Route Methods Summary

```
| Feature        | Hook / API          | Purpose                        |
|----------------|---------------------|--------------------------------|
| URL params     | useParams()         | :id segments                   |
| Query string   | useSearchParams()   | ?key=value pairs               |
| Navigate       | useNavigate()       | Programmatic navigation        |
| Current URL    | useLocation()       | Path, search, hash, state      |
| Loader data    | useLoaderData()     | Access pre-fetched route data  |
| Match check    | useMatch()          | Does URL match pattern?        |
| Nested render  | <Outlet />          | Render matched child route     |
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting `<Outlet />` in parent layout components — child routes render nowhere
- Using `window.location.href` instead of `navigate()` — causes full page reload, loses React state
- Not adding `replace: true` on post-login navigate — back button returns to login
- Loader errors: always handle 404/401 by throwing a Response and using errorElement
- Nesting routes incorrectly — a path without required parent path prefix won't match

## Connections
- **react-state-effects** — loader pattern replaces useEffect data fetching in routes
- **react-context** — protected routes use auth context to decide redirect
- **react-performance** — lazy loading route components with React.lazy + Suspense

